    <title>Combined summary - deterministic transaction expiration</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T01:50:54.910428+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-August/006399.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The issue of unconfirmed transactions in Bitcoin has been a long-standing concern for users, and there have been ongoing discussions among Bitcoin developers regarding the best approaches to address this issue. Various solutions have been proposed, including transaction expiration rules, adding information in the transaction itself, and refreshing the transaction's lifetime through child transactions. One proposal suggests using nLockTime for expiration, but concerns have been raised about existing uses of nLockTime becoming worthless. Another proposal involves adding finite and predictable lifespans to transactions in mempools using nLockTime and a new standardness rule. This proposal can be implemented in stages without requiring a soft fork. Additionally, there have been suggestions to create a new parallel transaction format where fields are committed by Merkle radix tree in an extensible and provable manner. However, some parties doubt that this approach is the best one.Developers have suggested implementing changes to nLockTime, such as setting it to the current height by default and adding an IsStandard rule rejecting transactions with an nLockTime more than N blocks behind the current tip. Discussions have also included adding a new field to the tx format using merkle radix trees, introducing a new script opcode that pushes the current block height onto the operand stack, and implementing transaction expiration rules whereby transactions drop out of mempools after a fixed number of blocks from their creation. Despite these proposals, some developers have expressed doubts about their effectiveness and potential risks.In an email conversation, Kaz Wesley expressed doubts about the approach of beginning a transaction expiry countdown when a transaction is received, stating it seems unviable. He suggests including information in the transaction itself, as with his nLockTime/IsStandard proposal, is necessary for transactions to reliably eventually die off from mempools. The current lack of transaction lifetime management in the network's mempools has been identified as a major factor blocking some mempool exchange. Jeff Garzik, a Bitcoin core developer and open source evangelist, agrees that the bitcoind Tx mempool size is rather open-ended and needs sorting out.The discussion revolves around the idea of using nLockTime for transaction expiration and its potential impact on payment channel refunds and other active uses of nLockTime. The issue of unconfirmed transactions in Bitcoin has been a long-standing concern for users. For now, capping the mempool's size at each local node is a more reachable goal, which implies some culling policy.Bitcoin developers have been discussing the introduction of a new field for expiration time to address the current lack of transaction lifetime management in the network's mempools. There are concerns about existing users and uses of nLockTime becoming worthless if a new field were to be introduced suddenly. Additionally, there is a proposal to add finite and predictable lifespans to transactions in mempools using nLockTime and a new standardness rule. This proposal could be achieved without requiring even a soft fork and would not cause problems with reorgs.Despite the potential benefits of various solutions, there are still challenges to consider, such as fee-sniping reorgs and the risk of invalidating transactions later due to chain reorganizations. However, by exploring various options and taking into account different viewpoints, the Bitcoin community can continue to work towards improving the user experience of unconfirmed transactions.</summary>
